In the C# language, string values are of type string. A string is an object of type String whose value is text. Text, in turn, is stored internally as a set of characters, for which there is their own type Char. We can say that a string is like a regular array, the elements of which are single characters.

Strings are created very simply, here is one of the most intuitive ways: string <variable name> = “<text>”;
Please note that the text must be enclosed in double quotes, while single quotes enclose single characters.It follows that variables of type Char use single quotes, and double quotes for String.A string variable can consist of a single character, but a character variable of several characters cannot .
